## Global Warming Analysis


### Part A. Daily vs Annual Temperature in NYC
#### Jan 10th vs Annual Avg

Analyzing the daily temperature in New York City on January 5th yielded a quite noisy data set. While the data
appeared to possibly have a positive slope, the r^2 of 0.05 indicated little association between the year and
temperature. Superficially this could suggest that temperatures have not changed over time. The ratio of standard error
to slope of 0.614 corresponds to an amount of variation in temperature that would not be statistically significant.
However, this is only one day of the year...

Analyzing the average temperature in NYC for 1961-2009 shows a slightly different story. Here the
scatterplot seemed to display a more clear positive, linear relationship between year and temperature. The r^2 statistic
of 0.189 is not alarmingly high by any means, but the ratio of the standard error to slope is much smaller in this case
and corresponds to statistically significant result.

The noise in both datasets demonstrates the inherent volatility of temperature. In the case of daily temperatures it
seems that even within the winter season, daily temperatures fluctuate considerably. On the yearly scale noise in
temperatures may be affected by seasonal fluctuations.

Overall, while the Jan 10th temperature data doesn't indicate a change in temperature, the yearly analysis presents
stronger evidence in favor of increased temperature. The average data considers a larger sample of days, taking each day
of the year from 1961-2009 rather than a single day

### Part B. Average City Temperature
#### Annual Temperature in Major USA Cities

The scatterplot for Year vs Avg City Temperature displays a strong, positive association and shows stronger
evidence of global warming during the timespan in the training data. In addition to the plot itself showing a stronger
relationship, the model produced a much higher r^2 of 0.746 and a much lower standard error to slope ratio. These
statistics strengthen the case that temperatures have increased over time. The scatter of points around the regression
line suggests that the relationship is not actually be linear despite the strong fit.

Analyzing New York City alone indicated some evidence for an increase in average temperature. The new plot demonstrates
increased average temperatures across all US cities in the data set. The larger sample of cities provides stronger
evidence; however, the cities are also located in a variety of geographic locations.

Had we only used 3 cities we would expect to also see an increase in avg temperature over time, but the results would be
more volatile due to a smaller sample size. We could see much higher or lower increases in average temperature depending
on which cities were chosen. This variability would likely decrease the r^2 value and increase the std error to slope
ratio (i.e. less reliable results). If we chose 100 cities we would expect the opposite to occur.

If cities from the same region were chosen, we could expect to see less variation in temperature within the cities.
However, the overall association between year and temperature could deviate considerably from the overall sample based
on particular factors of the region in question. Specific regions may have experienced smaller or larger changes in
average temperature in compared to the entire sample of cities.

### Part C. Annual Temperature: Moving Averages
#### City Temperature-- 5 Year Moving Average

A 5 year moving average for annual temperature across cities was computed for the training interval.
Plotting the 5 year moving average also shows a strong association between Year and Temperature-- the strongest so far.
The r^2 value of 0.925 is extremely high and the std error to slope ratio is very low. That being said the observations
appear to oscillate about the line. As a result, while there is a strong evidence of a strong, positive association
between Year and Temperature, the plot suggests a non-linear relationship.

The oscillations indicate some kind of natural pattern in average yearly temperature variation, but they may represent
random fluctuations. The latter seems unlikely although it is unclear what mechanism might cause temperature to
fluctuate in a consistent manner. Possibly some natural phenomenon...

In either case it appears that the average temperature in the training data has in fact increased over the time span in
the training data. Even though the plot does not form a line, the linear fit remains "strong" because the line captures
the increase in average temperature to a meaningful extent. We could use the line to establish the the temperature has
generally increased, but it may not suffice to predict future temperatures...

### Part D. Predicting the Future
#### Higher Degree Models

Here additional models of degree 2 and degree 20 were fit to the data and compared to the degree 1 model from part C.
The r^2 values of the models were 0.945 and 0.972 respectively, while the standard error to slope ratios were -3.08 and
4x10^53 (!!!). Assuming no calculation errors, these ratios are unusual-- in particular the degree 20 model ratio is
alarmingly high. These numbers suggest that while strong, the fit may due to chance despite the high r^2 values. That
being said more investigation is needed as to the interpretation of the standard error to slope ratio when applied to
higher degree models.

The degree 20 model has the strongest r^2. This is expected as the higher degree allows the function to map a curve more
closely to changes in the training data. However, overfitting is a major concern. Based on the r^2, the std error slope
ratios, and the plot itself the linear model seems to be the best fit.

#### Testing Models: RMSE

When testing models the Root Mean Squared Error (RSME) was computed rather than the r^2. This choice was made due to the
RSME retaining the scale of errors, while r^2 is standardized. Additionally, the course suggested that RMSE is generally
preferred over r^2 when testing out of sample data performance. This is due to interpretations and properties r^2
failing to translate when applied to models evaluated on data outside


The scatterplots of test data indicate that the degree 1 model outperforms both higher degree models. In particular the
training models for the degree 2 and degree 20 models were quite poor. Both of these models overestimated the test data
for *all* observations* indicating substantial bias. The RMSE values were

- 0.088 (Degree 1)
- 0.212 (Degree 2)
- 1.491 (Degree 20)

In addition to appearing most reasonable based on the scatterplots, the linear model also has the lowest RMSE by a
decent margin. However, the RMSE must be compared to the scale of data. Relevant statistics of the average 5 year moving
average in the test data set are

- mean: 16.94 degrees Celsius
- min: 16.75 degrees Celsius
- max: 17.09 degrees Celsius

With a data range of ~0.34 degrees Celsius we see that the RMSE of the degree 2 model is fairly large, while the RMSE of
the degree 20 model is extremely large-- over 4x the data range. The RMSE of the linear model appears reasonably small,
but warrants deeper analysis. We can safely conclude that the linear model performs best on test data by a wide margin
and that the higher degree models suffer from aforementioned overfitting.


*The r^2 value may have been negative for these models which indicates that the model does performs worse than simply
predicting the average. This is impossible when a model is used to evaluate *in sample* error. This scenario indicates
why one may prefer to use RMSE over r^2 on out of sample data.

#### Temperature Variation

Additionally, the claim that temperatures had become more volatile by analyzing the standard deviation of the 5 year
moving temperature average within the training data. Surprisingly, the scatterplot indicated a decrease in the standard
deviation of temperature. However, the r^2 was relatively low and the scatterplot and degree 1 model suggest bias within
the residuals. Still, there does seem to be evidence of a meaningful decrease in the standard deviation even if the
result is not appropriately modeled by a linear fit.

That being said analyzing the standard deviation of temperature averages may not properly reflect overall volatility. In
particular, the 5 year moving average would mitigate the impact of extreme temperatures in the sample. It is certainly
possible for the most *extreme* temperatures to have become hotter or colder while the average temperatures became more
consistent.

It would be more appropriate to analyze the minimum and maximum temperatures over time, perhaps some portion of upper
and lower percentiles. For instance we could average the lowest 5% of temperatures and highest 5% of temperatures and
fit these values over the training sample. Then following the method used previously we could also examine a moving
average.
